[5] Viet Nam
Date: Tue 10 Feb 2009
Source: VietNamNet Bridge [edited]
<http://english.vietnamnet.vn/social/2009/02/828021/>


There has been a 20.5 per cent increase in the incidence of petechial
fever [dengue fever] nationwide, compared to the same period last
year [2008], with about 3000 people affected already this year [2009].

Mosquitoes are the main carrier of the disease, which is dangerous
for babies and overweight children. It can lead to respiratory and
digestive problems.

Prolonged rain and poor living conditions, such as dirty houses
surrounded by lakes, ponds, and stagnant water, create favourable
breeding conditions for mosquitoes.

Ministry of Health spokesman Nguyen Huy Nga said southern Dong Nai
Province was the hardest hit, with more than 300 cases, followed by
Mekong Delta Tien Giang province with 290 cases.

Although the number of petechial fever [dengue fever] patients
increased, other diseases had fallen, including encephalitis (down 47
per cent), typhoid (20 per cent), and malaria (13.7 per cent).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MBDS <promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[As of 25 Nov 2008, a total of 78 512 cases and 79 fatalities from
dengue fever had been identified in Viet Nam during 2008 (see prior
PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (20) 20081126.3720). Nearly 14 000
cases of dengue fever were recorded in Ho Chi Minh City in 2008 (see
prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (21): Ho Chi Minh City
20081211.3891). As of 9 Feb 2009, Thailand has reported 1675 cases
and 2 deaths attributable to dengue fever so far this year. (see
prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Thailand 20090209.0590).

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
