[7] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Mon 16 Feb 2009
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25060545-2702,00.html


The number of dengue fever cases in north Queensland has passed 400,
as authorities fight 3 strains of the disease [dengue virus].
Queensland Health says 21 new cases were confirmed over the weekend,
17 in the Cairns area and 4 in the Townsville area.

Port Douglas in the state's far-north still has only one case of the
mosquito-borne disease, while no further cases of the troubling
dengue [virus] type 2 have been confirmed.

Last week, 2 Cairns patients were diagnosed with dengue type 2 [virus
infection], meaning authorities are fighting 3 strains of the disease
[dengue virus].

It has heightened concern around the outbreak, as people who have had
dengue are at risk of serious illnesses, even death, if they contract
another strain of the virus.

The number of dengue fever cases confirmed since the 1 Dec 2008
outbreak now stands at 418.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Dengue virus type 3 has been reported from Cairns (see ProMED
archive no. 20090113.0133) and dengue virus type 2 from Port Douglas,
but the 3rd dengue virus type involved in the Queensland outbreak has
not been mentioned.

